This convention is used to specify the boundary of a multipart request. It's useful when you want to use multiple content types within one request, such as text/plain and application/json. The boundary can be specified using either the `boundary` query parameter or the `Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=<boundary>` header.

```php
use Laminas\Diactoros\Request;

$request = Request::createFromGlobals();
// $request->getQueryParams()['boundary'] === 'my_boundary'; // true
$request->getHeaderLine('Content-Type') === 'multipart/form-data; boundary=my_boundary'; // true
```

## Details

Class | Description
---|---
[Laminas\\Diactoros\\Request](api-laminas-diactoros-request) | This class represents an HTTP request message.

## Usage

#### Using the `boundary` query parameter

```php
use Laminas\Diactoros\Request;

$queryParams = ['boundary' => 'my_boundary'];
$request = Request::createFromGlobals($queryParams);
```

#### Using the `Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=<boundary>` header

```php
use Laminas\Diactoros\Request;

$headers = [
    'Content-Type' => 'multipart/form-data; boundary=my_boundary',
];
$request = Request::createFromGlobals(null, null, $headers);
```

